window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>1>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"The table below shows an extract from balance of payments for country A  Use the table below to answer the question that follows:     Balance of payments Items    Items of transactions Receipts (N) Payment (N)1.  Merchandise (Visible trade) 52 000.00 40 000.00 2.  Shipping other transport and travel 4 000.00 8 000.00 3.   Investment income 20 000.00 5 000.004.  Other services 2 500.00 7 500.005.   Unrequired transfers 22 800.00 7 000.006.  Direct investment 50 000.00 26 000.007.  Other long-term capital 254 000.00 289 000.008. Short-term capital 221 000.00 238 000.00    Calculate the balance of trade","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Balance of trade = Export of goods - Imports of goods  =$52,000.00-$40,000.00  =$12,000.00","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>1>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"The table below shows an extract from balance of payments for country A  Use the table below to answer the question that follows:     Balance of payments Items    Items of transactions Receipts (N) Payment (N)1.  Merchandise (Visible trade) 52 000.00 40 000.00 2.  Shipping other transport and travel 4 000.00 8 000.00 3.   Investment income 20 000.00 5 000.004.  Other services 2 500.00 7 500.005.   Unrequired transfers 22 800.00 7 000.006.  Direct investment 50 000.00 26 000.007.  Other long-term capital 254 000.00 289 000.008. Short-term capital 221 000.00 238 000.00  Calculate the balance on current account","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Credit items = $52,000.00 + $4,000.00 + $20,000.00 + $2,500.00 + $22,800   = $101,300.00  Debit items = $40,000.00 + $8,000.00 + $5,000.00 + $7,500.00 + $7,000.00   = $67,500.00  Balance on current account = $101,300.00 - $67,500.00   = $33,800.00","marks":"8","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>1>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"The table below shows an extract from balance of payments for country A  Use the table below to answer the question that follows:     Balance of payments Items    Items of transactions Receipts (N) Payment (N)1.  Merchandise (Visible trade) 52 000.00 40 000.00 2.  Shipping other transport and travel 4 000.00 8 000.00 3.   Investment income 20 000.00 5 000.004.  Other services 2 500.00 7 500.005.   Unrequired transfers 22 800.00 7 000.006.  Direct investment 50 000.00 26 000.007.  Other long-term capital 254 000.00 289 000.008. Short-term capital 221 000.00 238 000.00  Calculate the balance on capital account","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Credit items = $50,000.00 + $254,000.00 + $221,000.00   = $553,000.00  Balance on capital account = $525,000.00 - $553,000.00   = -$28,000.00","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>1>d","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"The table below shows an extract from balance of payments for country A  Use the table below to answer the question that follows:     Balance of payments Items    Items of transactions Receipts (N) Payment (N)1.  Merchandise (Visible trade) 52 000.00 40 000.00 2.  Shipping other transport and travel 4 000.00 8 000.00 3.   Investment income 20 000.00 5 000.004.  Other services 2 500.00 7 500.005.   Unrequired transfers 22 800.00 7 000.006.  Direct investment 50 000.00 26 000.007.  Other long-term capital 254 000.00 289 000.008. Short-term capital 221 000.00 238 000.00  Calculate the balance of payment","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Balance of payments = Balance on current account + Balance on capital account   = ($33,800.00) + (-$28,000.00)    = $33,800.00 - $28,000   = $5,800.00","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>2>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : ELASTICITY OF SUPPLY","question":"The table below presents the price and quality supplied by a palm oil producer.   Use the information in the table to answer the following question.   Price (N) Quantity Supplied (gallons)6 20012 30018 40020 50024 600  If the price of palm oil falls from N20.00 to N18.00, calculate the price elasticity of supply.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Priceelasticityofsupply=\u2206Q\u2206P\u00d7PQ  P = $20.00  Q = 500 gallons  \u2206Q = 500 - 400 = 100 gallons  \u2206P = $20.00 - $18.00 = $2.00  Es=1002\u00d720500  Es = 2","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>2>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : ELASTICITY OF SUPPLY","question":"Interpret your answer in question 2(a) above","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The supply is elastic.  This is because the coefficient of price elasticity of supply is greater than one (Es > 1)","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>2>c>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Study the extract below and answer the following questions.   The price of palm oil remains at N6.00 per gallon and an increase in the price of a related product causes an increase in the supply of palm oil.    Give graphical presentation to illustrate this change","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>2>c>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : TYPES OF SUPPLY","question":"Study the extract below and answer the following questions.   The price of palm oil remains at N6.00 per gallon and an increase in the price of a related product causes an increase in the supply of palm oil.    Indicate the type of supply for the two products","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Joint supply i.e these two products are jointly supplied","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>2>d","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"State three reasons that can cause a change in supply","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Change in the price of related products  - Cost of production  - Change in technology  - Government policy e.g tax or subsidy  - Expectations of producers   - Number of producers  - Weather condition  - Natural disaster","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>3>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"Define occupation mobility of labour","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Occupation mobility of labour is the ease with which a worker or labour moves from one occupation or job to another","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>3>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"Identify any four barriers to occupational mobility of labour efficient","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Natural abilities required in certain occupation may prevent such labour from moving e.g musicians, artists  - Cost of training may be high  - Trade union or professional association may inhibit such movements  - Labour may be too old to learn new skills  - Differences in remuneration may prevent labour from moving from one occupation to another  - Discrimination on account of sex or race in some places may prevent mobility  - Inadequate information about wage rates and opportunities in other occupations   - Training may take a long period of time","marks":"12","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>3>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"State any 2 factors that will make labour efficient","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Education and training: e.g formal education and on-the-job training.  - Good remuneration: Higher wages and salaries serve to motivate the worker to work harder.  - Good work environment: Good ventilation, good furnishing etc will make labour more efficient.  - Good management style: A good management style encourages working efficient.","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>4>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : INTRODUCTION","question":"What is crop farming?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Crop farming is the growing of cash crops such as cocoa, cotton, groundnut, and the growing of food crops such as rice, cassava, beans, yam etc.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>4>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : FEATURES","question":"Outline any four measures that can be adopted to increase crops production in your country","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- The education of farmers to eradicate illiteracy  - Provision of finance through the establishment of agricultural bank   - Measures to effectively control pests and disease  - Provision of infrastructural facilities to reduce rural-urban migration open rural areas for trade  - Land reforms that will make land available for large scale farming  - Establishment of research centers to conduct research into various production  - Extension services  - Payment of attractive prices to producers   - Provision of tools and machinery at subsidized rates  - Provision of irrigation facilities to encourage all-year farming.","marks":"12","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>4>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : ROLES","question":"State any two contributions of the industrial sectors agriculture in your country","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Industrial sector manufactures farm implements such as hoes and cutlass  - Industrial sector manufactures agrochemicals and fertilizers  - It provides ready markets for agricultural raw materials  - It provides variety of goods for the farmers to patronize  - Industrial sector promotes research and training in the use of their products  - Industrial sector absorbs excess labour from the agricultural sector.","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>5>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : LIMITED LIABILITY COMPANIES","question":"Highlight any four differences between a public liability company any a private limited liability company","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Public limited company can be formed by a minimum of two members with no maximum while a private limited company can be formed by a minimum of two members and a maximum of fifty members  - Public limited company publishes its accounts to the public while a private limited company is not obliged to do so.  - Shareholders can freely transfer their shares in public limited company while shareholders cannot freely transfer their shares without the consent of other shareholders in a private limited company.  - Public limited company can obtain loans more easily from financial institutions than private limited company.  - Members of the public can be invited to subscribe to shares in a public limited company while members of the public cannot be invited to subscribe to shares in a private limited company.","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>5>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : LIMITED LIABILITY COMPANIES","question":"Explain any four advantages of a limited liability company","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Limited liability: The maximum loss of a shareholder cannot exceed his contribution to the share capital.  - Greater degree of continuity: Death or withdrawal of a shareholder does not affect the existence of the business  - Greater access to capital: A limited liability company can easily access more capital through loans, issuance and sale of shares.  - Ownership is separated from control: It is owned by shareholders but controlled and managed by board of directors.  - Usually large size and employs more people.  - It is a legal entity: It can sue and be sued in its own name.  - Experts can be employed to manage the business: The best hands can be employed as a result of its huge resources.","marks":"12","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>6>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT","question":"Define gross national income","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Gross national income is the money value of all final goods and services produced in an economy in a given period plus net factor income from abroad.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>6>b>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT","question":"Using appropriate examples, distinguish between Personal income and disposal income","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Personal income is the amount earned by an individual for taking part in the production of goods and services either by him or his property e.g wages, interest, rent and profit.  Disposable income on the other hand is what individuals have to spend after personal income tax has been deducted from their personal income i.e disposable income equals personal income less personal income tax.","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>6>b>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT","question":"Using appropriate examples, distinguish between Nominal income and real income","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Nominal income is the value of all goods and services produced expressed in terms of current money income received from their production.  Real income on the other and is nominal income expressed in terms of what is can buy. It is the nominal income deflated by the price level.","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>6>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : USES & REASONS FOR MEASURING NATIONAL INCOME","question":"Outline any three uses of national income statistics","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- It is used for economic planning  - It is used as a basis for aids and grants from other countries   - It is useful in the calculation of per capita income  - It is used for internation comparison of standard of living  - It allows for sectoral comparison  - It allows for intertemporal comparison  - It influences foreign investments  - It is used as a basis for contribution to international organizations  - It is used to measure the level of economic performance i.e whether the economy is growing or not.","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>7>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : INTRODUCTION","question":"What is the normal chain of distribution?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Producers \u2192 Wholesalers \u2192 Retailers \u2192 Consumers","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>7>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE MIDDLEMEN","question":"State any three functions of middlemen in the chain of distribution","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- provide warehousing facilities  - Help of finance production  - Give credit facility to the retailer  - Breaking the bulk   - Provide information to the producers  - Repackaging  - Providing varieties of goods  - Provide after-sales services","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>7>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : MARKETING BOARDS","question":"Highlight any four problems involved in the distribution of goods in West Africa","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Large number of middlemen makes distribution complex. Consumers are made to pay high prices because of profit mark-up by numerous middlemen.  - Inadequate capital/credit facilities make distributive trade to be mostly on small scale  - Poor storage facilities make it difficult for distributors to even-out supply. This usually leads to high product prices at certain periods.  - Hoarding of goods to create artificial scarcity.  - Inadequate information about existence of market for products  - Poor transport network which results in high cost of transportation  - Difference in weights and measures make product pricing difficult.","marks":"12","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>8>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"What is a specific tax?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A specific tax is a ta that is levied at a fixed rate per unit of output.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>8>b>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX","question":"Explain with the aid of diagrams, the effects of specific tax on a commodity that has a perfect elastic demand","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"A specific tax is a cost of production, the effect is a reduction in supply from S1S1 to S2S2 by the amount of tax as in the diagram below.  A reduction in supply cannot lead to an increase in price because the demand for the commodity is perfectly price elastic.  The entire burden of a specific tax falls on the producer who is unable to increase his price. Equilibrium quantity falls from q2 to q1 while price remains the same.","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>8>b>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX","question":"Explain with the aid of diagrams, the effects of specific tax on a commodity that has a perfect inelastic demand","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"A specific tax will make the market price of a commodity that has a perfectly inelastic demand to rise by the full amount of the tax.  Since the demand is perfectly inelastic, quantity demanded will remain the same i.e Q1 while the price of the commodity will increase by the full amount of the tax e.g from P1 to P2.","marks":"6","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2014>8>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2014","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"State two difference between a direct tax and an indirect tax","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- A direct tax is levied on an individual's income or property while an indirect tax is paid indirectly when an individual purchases goods and services.  - A direct tax can be evaded while indirect tax cannot be evaded  - A direct tax can serve as a disincentive to work while indirect tax may not  - A direct tax can be progressive while indirect tax is usually regressive  - Generally, indirect tax is more convenient to collect than direct tax","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"}];